2. Phase 1: Foundation Architecture (2025-2026)

2.1 Q1 2025: Core Technology Development

2.1.1 Quantum Computing Stack

```
Week 1-4: Quantum Processor Design
  - Task 1.1: Finalize QE-1024 architecture (logical qubits)
  - Task 1.2: Design cryogenic system for 10 mK operation
  - Task 1.3: Develop control electronics for 1024 qubits
  - Deliverable: Complete quantum processor design documents
  - Resources: 10 quantum engineers, $5M budget

Week 5-8: Quantum Software Framework
  - Task 2.1: Implement quantum error correction (surface-21 code)
  - Task 2.2: Develop quantum compiler for energy applications
  - Task 2.3: Create quantum simulation environment
  - Deliverable: QuantumSDK v1.0 with energy-specific libraries
  - Resources: 15 quantum software engineers, $3M budget

Week 9-12: Quantum Algorithms Development
  - Task 3.1: Implement quantum power flow algorithm
  - Task 3.2: Develop quantum state estimation
  - Task 3.3: Create quantum contingency analysis
  - Deliverable: QuantumEnergyLib v1.0 with 10+ algorithms
  - Resources: 8 quantum algorithm specialists, $2M budget
```

2.1.2 Neuromorphic Computing Stack

```
Week 1-4: Neuromorphic Chip Design
  - Task 4.1: Finalize NE-20M architecture (20M neurons)
  - Task 4.2: Design spike-timing-dependent plasticity circuits
  - Task 4.3: Develop on-chip learning mechanisms
  - Deliverable: Neuromorphic processor tape-out ready
  - Resources: 12 neuromorphic engineers, $4M budget

Week 5-8: Neuromorphic Software Stack
  - Task 5.1: Implement Nengo compiler for energy applications
  - Task 5.2: Develop spiking neural network libraries
  - Task 5.3: Create neuromorphic simulation framework
  - Deliverable: NeuroEnergySDK v1.0
  - Resources: 10 neuromorphic software engineers, $2M budget

Week 9-12: Neuromorphic Applications
  - Task 6.1: Implement predictive load forecasting SNN
  - Task 6.2: Develop anomaly detection network
  - Task 6.3: Create grid control cerebellum model
  - Deliverable: 5 working neuromorphic applications
  - Resources: 6 application engineers, $1M budget
```

2.1.3 Hybrid Architecture Development

```
Week 1-8: Hybrid Integration Framework
  - Task 7.1: Design quantum-neuromorphic interface protocol
  - Task 7.2: Develop co-processing scheduling algorithms
  - Task 7.3: Create shared memory architecture
  - Deliverable: HybridProcessingFramework v1.0
  - Resources: 8 systems architects, $3M budget

Week 9-12: Energy Optimization Engine
  - Task 8.1: Implement Triad AI architecture (Vulcan, Sol, Terra)
  - Task 8.2: Develop multi-scale optimization algorithms
  - Task 8.3: Create real-time decision framework
  - Deliverable: EnergyOptimizationEngine v1.0
  - Resources: 10 AI/ML engineers, $2M budget
```

2.2 Q2 2025: Infrastructure Development

2.2.1 Data Center Design & Build

```
Month 4-6: Quantum Computing Facility
  - Location: Nevada, USA (geologically stable, low humidity)
  - Size: 10,000 sq ft purpose-built facility
  - Power: 10 MW dedicated, 2N+1 redundancy
  - Cooling: Custom dilution refrigerator infrastructure
  - Security: SCIF-level physical security
  - Cost: $20M construction, $10M equipment
  - Timeline: 6 months design/build
  - Resources: Construction team, quantum facility engineers

Month 4-6: Neuromorphic Computing Facility
  - Location: Texas, USA (access to talent, energy)
  - Size: 5,000 sq ft high-performance computing center
  - Power: 5 MW, N+1 redundancy
  - Cooling: Direct liquid cooling for neuromorphic chips
  - Network: 100 Gbps redundant fiber connections
  - Cost: $10M construction, $5M equipment
  - Timeline: 4 months build-out
  - Resources: Data center specialists, network engineers
```

2.2.2 Communication Network Implementation

```
Month 4-6: Quantum Network Backbone
  - Task 9.1: Deploy 100 km quantum key distribution testbed
  - Task 9.2: Install 10 quantum network nodes
  - Task 9.3: Implement quantum repeater prototype
  - Deliverable: QuantumNetwork v1.0 with 10 nodes
  - Resources: 6 quantum network engineers, $5M budget

Month 4-6: Classical Network Infrastructure
  - Task 10.1: Deploy 400 Gbps fiber backbone (100 km)
  - Task 10.2: Install 5G private network for edge devices
  - Task 10.3: Implement time-sensitive networking switches
  - Deliverable: EnergyNetwork v1.0 with <1 ms latency
  - Resources: 8 network engineers, $3M budget
```

2.3 Q3 2025: Pilot System Integration

2.3.1 First Hybrid Processing Node

```
Week 25-28: Hardware Integration
  - Task 11.1: Assemble QE-1024 quantum processor
  - Task 11.2: Integrate NE-20M neuromorphic processors (4×)
  - Task 11.3: Install classical compute (NVIDIA Grace-Hopper)
  - Task 11.4: Connect via high-speed optical interconnects
  - Deliverable: First working hybrid processing node
  - Resources: 15 hardware engineers, $10M equipment

Week 29-32: Software Integration
  - Task 12.1: Install EnergyOS microkernel
  - Task 12.2: Deploy container orchestration (Kubernetes)
  - Task 12.3: Implement quantum-neuromorphic co-processing
  - Task 12.4: Integrate Triad AI agents
  - Deliverable: Fully integrated software stack
  - Resources: 10 systems engineers, $2M budget

Week 33-36: System Validation
  - Task 13.1: Performance benchmarking (quantum vs classical)
  - Task 13.2: Stability testing (7-day continuous operation)
  - Task 13.3: Security validation (penetration testing)
  - Task 13.4: Energy efficiency measurement
  - Deliverable: Certified hybrid processing node
  - Resources: QA team, security team, $1M budget
```

2.3.2 Energy Infrastructure Integration

```
Month 7-9: Grid Interface Development
  - Task 14.1: Implement IEC 61850 protocol stack
  - Task 14.2: Develop PMU (phasor measurement unit) interface
  - Task 14.3: Create SCADA integration layer
  - Deliverable: GridInterface v1.0 supporting 10+ protocols
  - Resources: 6 power systems engineers, $1M budget

Month 7-9: Renewable Energy Integration
  - Task 15.1: Connect to 100 MW solar farm (pilot site)
  - Task 15.2: Integrate 50 MW wind farm
  - Task 15.3: Interface with 100 MWh battery storage
  - Deliverable: RenewableIntegration v1.0
  - Resources: 4 renewable energy engineers, $500K budget
```

2.4 Q4 2025: First Pilot Deployment

2.4.1 10-Node Test Network

```
Week 37-40: Node Deployment
  - Location 1: Quantum facility (Nevada) - Hub node
  - Location 2: Neuromorphic facility (Texas) - Hub node
  - Location 3: Solar farm (California) - Edge node
  - Location 4: Wind farm (Texas) - Edge node
  - Location 5: Substation (Arizona) - Edge node
  - Location 6-10: Additional test sites

Each Node Configuration:
  - Quantum: 32-128 qubit processors (smaller than hub)
  - Neuromorphic: 1-5M neuron processors
  - Classical: NVIDIA Jetson or similar
  - Communication: 10 Gbps fiber, 5G wireless backup
  - Power: Local renewable + grid connection
  - Cost: $500K-$2M per node depending on capabilities

Deployment Process:
  - Day 1-7: Site preparation and power/network installation
  - Day 8-14: Hardware installation and basic testing
  - Day 15-21: Software deployment and configuration
  - Day 22-28: Integration testing with central system
  - Day 29-35: Load testing and optimization
  - Day 36-42: Security hardening and final validation
```

2.4.2 Initial Capabilities Deployment

```
Capability 1: Real-Time Grid Monitoring
  - Sensors: 1000+ points across test network
  - Data Rate: 1 million measurements/second
  - Latency: < 100 ms from sensor to dashboard
  - Visualization: Real-time 3D grid visualization
  - Alerting: Automated anomaly detection

Capability 2: Predictive Maintenance
  - Assets Monitored: Transformers, breakers, lines, inverters
  - Prediction Horizon: 24-72 hours before failure
  - Accuracy Target: 90% true positive rate
  - Actions: Automated work order generation

Capability 3: Renewable Optimization
  - Solar Forecasting: 24-hour ahead, 95% accuracy
  - Wind Forecasting: 24-hour ahead, 90% accuracy
  - Storage Optimization: Charge/discharge scheduling
  - Economic Dispatch: 5-minute intervals

Capability 4: Carbon Accounting
  - Measurement: Real-time carbon intensity calculation
  - Tracking: From generation to consumption
  - Verification: Blockchain-based immutable records
  - Reporting: Automated compliance reporting
```

2.5 2026: Scale to 100 Nodes

2.5.1 Manufacturing Scale-Up

```
Month 13-18: Quantum Processor Production
  - Facility: Clean room expansion (Class 100)
  - Capacity: 10 QE-1024 processors/month
  - Yield Target: 70% for full 1024-qubit processors
  - Cost Reduction: From $10M to $2M per processor
  - Quality: 99.999% gate fidelity maintained
  - Resources: 20 manufacturing engineers, $50M capex

Month 13-18: Neuromorphic Chip Production
  - Foundry: TSMC 5nm process
  - Capacity: 100 NE-20M chips/month
  - Yield Target: 90% for functional chips
  - Cost Reduction: From $100K to $10K per chip
  - Quality: 20M neurons with 2B synapses functional
  - Resources: 15 semiconductor engineers, $20M capex

Month 13-18: Edge Node Manufacturing
  - Design: Standardized 19" rackmount or outdoor enclosure
  - Components: Quantum (32-128 qubits), neuromorphic (1-5M neurons), classical compute
  - Production: Contract manufacturing with Foxconn
  - Capacity: 50 nodes/month
  - Cost: $100K per edge node at scale
  - Resources: Supply chain team, manufacturing partners
```

2.5.2 Geographic Expansion

```
Region 1: Western USA (40 nodes)
  - California: 15 nodes (solar, grid, storage)
  - Nevada: 10 nodes (quantum, solar, transmission)
  - Arizona: 10 nodes (solar, load centers)
  - Pacific Northwest: 5 nodes (hydro, wind)

Region 2: Texas Grid (30 nodes)
  - ERCOT coverage: 30 nodes across Texas
  - Focus: Wind integration, grid stability, market optimization

Region 3: Europe Pilot (20 nodes)
  - Germany: 10 nodes (solar, wind, industrial load)
  - Netherlands: 5 nodes (wind, grid interconnection)
  - Scandinavia: 5 nodes (hydro, data centers)

Region 4: Asia Pilot (10 nodes)
  - Japan: 5 nodes (solar, storage, earthquake resilience)
  - Singapore: 5 nodes (urban grid, data centers)
```

2.5.3 Capability Enhancement

```
Enhancement 1: Quantum Optimization at Scale
  - Problem Size: 10,000-bus power systems
  - Solution Time: < 1 second for real-time optimization
  - Accuracy: 99.9% optimal vs exhaustive search
  - Applications: Continent-scale economic dispatch

Enhancement 2: Neuromorphic Anomaly Detection
  - Events Detected: Cyber attacks, physical faults, natural disasters
  - Detection Time: < 10 ms from event initiation
  - False Positive Rate: < 0.001%
  - Coverage: 100% of monitored infrastructure

Enhancement 3: Hybrid Forecasting
  - Load Forecasting: 24-hour ahead, 99% accuracy
  - Renewable Forecasting: 24-hour ahead, 98% accuracy
  - Price Forecasting: Day-ahead market, 95% accuracy
  - Extreme Event Prediction: 72-hour ahead severe weather

Enhancement 4: Autonomous Grid Control
  - Frequency Control: Maintain 60.00 Hz ± 0.001 Hz
  - Voltage Control: Maintain nominal ±0.5%
  - Emergency Response: < 100 ms for critical events
  - Self-Healing: Automatic restoration after outages
```

2.6 Phase 1 Milestones & Exit Criteria

2.6.1 Technical Milestones

```
M1.1: Quantum Processor Operational (Q2 2025)
  - 1024 logical qubits with error correction
  - 99.999% single-qubit gate fidelity
  - 500 μs coherence time
  - Exit Criteria: 7-day continuous operation without manual intervention

M1.2: Neuromorphic Processor Operational (Q2 2025)
  - 20 million silicon neurons
  - 2 billion configurable synapses
  - 10¹⁵ events/second processing
  - Exit Criteria: Real-time learning demonstrated on grid data

M1.3: Hybrid Node Integration (Q3 2025)
  - Quantum-neuromorphic co-processing
  - < 10 μs latency between processing paradigms
  - Energy efficiency: 100× better than classical alone
  - Exit Criteria: Joint optimization problem solved 1000× faster

M1.4: 10-Node Network Operational (Q4 2025)
  - All nodes communicating and coordinating
  - Real-time grid optimization demonstrated
  - 99.9% availability across network
  - Exit Criteria: 30-day continuous operation with zero critical failures

M1.5: 100-Node Network Operational (Q4 2026)
  - Geographic distribution across 4 regions
  - Multi-region coordination demonstrated
  - 99.99% availability across network
  - Exit Criteria: Handling 10 GW of generation and load
```

2.6.2 Business Milestones

```
B1.1: First Revenue (Q1 2026)
  - Contract: Grid optimization service for 1 utility
  - Value: $1M annual contract
  - Scope: 5 GW generation, 10,000 km transmission
  - Exit Criteria: Contract signed and implementation begun

B1.2: 10 Utility Contracts (Q4 2026)
  - Total Contract Value: $50M annual recurring revenue
  - Coverage: 50 GW generation capacity
  - Geographic: 3 countries, 2 continents
  - Exit Criteria: All contracts implemented and operational

B1.3: Carbon Credits Issued (Q3 2026)
  - Volume: 1 million tons CO₂ equivalent
  - Verification: Third-party verified methodology
  - Market: Sold at $100/ton average
  - Exit Criteria: Revenue received, methodology certified

B1.4: Series B Funding (Q4 2026)
  - Amount: $400M
  - Valuation: $2B
  - Lead Investor: Climate tech megafund
  - Exit Criteria: Funds received, expansion plan funded
```

2.6.3 Impact Milestones

```
I1.1: Carbon Reduction (Q4 2026)
  - Direct: 1 million tons CO₂ removed through optimization
  - Indirect: 10 million tons CO₂ avoided through efficiency
  - Measurement: Real-time tracking with blockchain verification
  - Exit Criteria: Third-party verified impact report

I1.2: Grid Stability Improvement (Q4 2026)
  - Frequency Stability: 60.00 Hz ± 0.01 Hz (from ±0.1 Hz)
  - Outage Reduction: 50% reduction in duration
  - Renewable Integration: 50% penetration achieved
  - Exit Criteria: Utility performance reports showing improvement

I1.3: Energy Access (Q4 2026)
  - Communities Served: 100 remote communities
  - People Impacted: 1 million people with improved access
  - Cost Reduction: 50% reduction in energy costs for served communities
  - Exit Criteria: Impact assessment report from independent NGO
```

