4.2 2031: Climate Intervention Systems

4.2.1 Direct Air Capture Network

```
System: DAC-1000 (1000 tons CO₂/day per unit)
  - Technology: Solid sorbent with low-temperature regeneration
  - Energy Source: Excess renewable energy (curtailed)
  - Efficiency: 0.4 MWh/ton CO₂ (industry leading)
  - Cost: $100/ton CO₂ at scale
  - Deployment: 1000 units globally by 2031
  - Total Capacity: 1 million tons CO₂/year
  - Integration: Controlled by ENERGOS optimization

Location Strategy:
  - Renewable-rich areas: Use excess solar/wind
  - Industrial areas: Co-locate with point sources
  - Strategic locations: Near storage/utilization sites
  - Global distribution: Proportional to historical emissions

Operation:
  - Scheduling: Run when renewable energy is abundant/curtailed
  - Optimization: Quantum optimization of DAC network
  - Monitoring: Real-time CO₂ capture measurement
  - Verification: Blockchain-based carbon credit issuance
```

4.2.2 Ocean-Based Carbon Removal

```
System: Ocean Alkalinity Enhancement
  - Technology: Electrochemical ocean alkalinity enhancement
  - Scale: 1 million tons CO₂/year per facility
  - Energy: 1 MWh/ton CO₂
  - Byproducts: Hydrogen and minerals
  - Environmental Impact: Positive (reduces ocean acidification)
  - Deployment: 10 facilities globally by 2031
  - Total Capacity: 10 million tons CO₂/year

Location Criteria:
  - Coastal areas with access to seawater
  - Renewable energy availability
  - Oceanographic conditions favorable for dispersion
  - Regulatory approval for marine operations

Monitoring:
  - Ocean Sensors: pH, alkalinity, carbonate chemistry
  - Satellite: Ocean color for phytoplankton response
  - Modeling: Ocean circulation and carbon sequestration
  - Verification: Third-party ocean carbon accounting
```

4.2.3 Enhanced Weathering

