5.2 2034: Climate Stabilization Systems

5.2.1 Gigaton-Scale Carbon Removal

```
Target: 1 gigaton CO₂ per year removal
Technologies:
  - Direct Air Capture: 500 million tons/year (5000× DAC-1000 units)
  - Ocean Alkalinity: 300 million tons/year (300 facilities)
  - Enhanced Weathering: 200 million tons/year (global deployment)
  - Total: 1 billion tons CO₂/year

Energy Requirements:
  - Total: 1 PWh/year (10% of global electricity)
  - Source: Excess renewable + dedicated fusion
  - Optimization: Quantum scheduling for minimum cost

Infrastructure:
  - DAC Facilities: 5000 globally distributed
  - Ocean Facilities: 300 coastal locations
  - Weathering Operations: Global agricultural integration
  - Storage: Geological sequestration + utilization
  - Cost: $100/ton average, $100B/year total
```

5.2.2 Solar Radiation Management

```
System: Marine Cloud Brightening
  - Technology: Salt aerosol generation from ocean vessels
  - Scale: 1% increase in cloud albedo
  - Effect: 1°C global cooling
  - Deployment: 1000 autonomous vessels globally
  - Control: Quantum-optimized spraying patterns
  - Monitoring: Satellite measurement of cloud properties
  - Cost: $1B/year operational

Precautionary Principles:
  - Gradual: Start with 0.1% effect, monitor carefully
  - Reversible: Can be stopped immediately if issues
  - Localized: Focus on regions most needing cooling
  - Governed: International oversight and approval
```

5.2.3 Arctic Restoration

```
System: Arctic Ice Protection and Restoration
  - Technologies:
    - Ocean wave pumps to bring deeper cold water to surface
    - Thin glass microspheres to increase ice albedo
    - Underwater curtains to slow warm water inflow
  - Scale: Stabilize and regrow Arctic sea ice
  - Energy: 10 GW dedicated power
  - Control: Quantum optimization of multiple techniques
  - Monitoring: Satellite and in-situ sensors
  - Cost: $10B initial, $1B/year operational
```

