6. Development Methodology & Practices

6.1 Agile at Scale Framework

6.1.1 Team Structure

```
Quantum Team (150 people):
  - Hardware (50): Qubit design, cryogenics, control electronics
  - Software (50): Quantum algorithms, error correction, simulation
  - Applications (30): Energy-specific quantum applications
  - Integration (20): Quantum-classical integration

Neuromorphic Team (100 people):
  - Hardware (30): Chip design, analog circuits, packaging
  - Software (40): SNN frameworks, learning algorithms, simulation
  - Applications (20): Grid-specific neuromorphic applications
  - Integration (10): Neuromorphic-quantum integration

Energy Systems Team (200 people):
  - Grid Integration (50): Power systems, protection, control
  - Renewables (50): Solar, wind, storage integration
  - Markets (30): Energy markets, trading, settlement
  - Infrastructure (70): Physical deployment, commissioning

AI/ML Team (100 people):
  - Algorithms (40): Optimization, forecasting, anomaly detection
  - Infrastructure (30): ML pipelines, feature stores, model serving
  - Applications (20): Triad AI agents, specialized models
  - Ethics (10): AI safety, fairness, transparency

Platform Team (150 people):
  - Core Systems (50): EnergyOS, container platform, orchestration
  - Data Platform (40): Ingestion, storage, processing, analytics
  - Network (30): Quantum and classical networking
  - Security (30): Cybersecurity, physical security, compliance

Operations Team (200 people):
  - Deployment (50): Site surveys, installation, commissioning
  - Support (100): 24/7 monitoring, incident response, customer support
  - Maintenance (50): Predictive maintenance, repairs, upgrades
```

6.1.2 Development Sprints

```
Sprint Length: 2 weeks
Synchronization: All teams aligned to same sprint schedule
Planning: 4-hour sprint planning at start
Review: 2-hour sprint review at end
Retrospective: 1-hour retrospective for continuous improvement

Artifacts:
  - Product Backlog: Prioritized list of all work
  - Sprint Backlog: Work committed for current sprint
  - Increment: Working software at end of each sprint
  - Burndown Charts: Visual progress tracking
  - Velocity: Historical completion rate for planning
```

6.1.3 Continuous Delivery Pipeline

```
Stage 1: Development
  - Environment: Local development with containers
  - Testing: Unit tests, integration tests, code quality
  - Artifacts: Container images, configuration, documentation

Stage 2: Integration
  - Environment: Shared integration environment
  - Testing: System integration, performance, security scanning
  - Validation: End-to-end scenarios, compatibility testing

Stage 3: Staging
  - Environment: Production-like but isolated
  - Testing: Load testing, failure testing, disaster recovery
  - Validation: User acceptance, operational acceptance

Stage 4: Production
  - Deployment: Blue-green or canary deployment
  - Monitoring: Real-time monitoring and alerting
  - Rollback: Automatic rollback on failure detection

Pipeline Speed:
  - Development to Integration: Multiple times per day
  - Integration to Staging: Daily
  - Staging to Production: Weekly for features, immediate for fixes
```

6.2 Quality Assurance Framework

6.2.1 Testing Strategy

```
Unit Testing (Developer Responsibility):
  - Coverage: > 90% for all new code
  - Automation: Run on every commit
  - Tools: pytest (Python), JUnit (Java), Go test (Go)

Integration Testing (QA Team):
  - Scope: Interfaces between components
  - Automation: API testing, contract testing
  - Coverage: All public interfaces
  - Tools: Postman, Karate, Pact

System Testing (QA Team):
  - Scope: Complete system functionality
  - Scenarios: End-to-end user scenarios
  - Environment: Production-like test environment
  - Tools: Selenium, Cypress, LoadRunner

Performance Testing (Performance Team):
  - Load Testing: Simulated production loads
  - Stress Testing: Beyond production loads
  - Endurance Testing: 7-day continuous operation
  - Tools: Locust, JMeter, Gatling

Security Testing (Security Team):
  - Static Analysis: Code scanning for vulnerabilities
  - Dynamic Analysis: Running system penetration testing
  - Dependency Scanning: Third-party library vulnerabilities
  - Tools: SonarQube, OWASP ZAP, Snyk

Quantum-Specific Testing (Quantum Team):
  - Algorithm Verification: Compare with classical solutions
  - Error Rate Measurement: Continuous monitoring of qubit performance
  - Stability Testing: Long-term operation under varying conditions
  - Tools: Custom quantum test frameworks
```

6.2.2 Quality Gates

```
Gate 1: Code Quality
  - Static Analysis: Zero critical vulnerabilities
  - Test Coverage: > 90% for new code
  - Code Review: All code reviewed by at least one other engineer
  - Documentation: All public APIs documented

Gate 2: Integration Quality
  - Integration Tests: 100% pass rate
  - Performance: Meets or exceeds performance targets
  - Compatibility: Works with all supported platforms
  - Security: No medium or high vulnerabilities

Gate 3: Release Quality
  - System Tests: 100% pass rate
  - Performance Tests: Meets production load requirements
  - Security Tests: Penetration testing passed
  - User Acceptance: Signed off by product owners
  - Operational Readiness: Signed off by operations team
```

6.3 Documentation Framework

6.3.1 Documentation Hierarchy

```
Level 1: Strategic (Executive)
  - Vision and strategy documents
  - Business plans and roadmaps
  - High-level architecture overviews
  - Audience: Executives, investors, partners

Level 2: Architectural (Technical Leadership)
  - System architecture specifications
  - API specifications and contracts
  - Data models and schemas
  - Security architecture
  - Audience: Architects, technical leads

Level 3: Implementation (Development Teams)
  - Component design documents
  - API reference documentation
  - Database schemas and queries
  - Deployment procedures
  - Audience: Developers, QA engineers

Level 4: Operational (Operations Teams)
  - Installation guides
  - Configuration guides
  - Troubleshooting guides
  - Maintenance procedures
  - Audience: System administrators, support engineers

Level 5: User (End Users)
  - User manuals and guides
  - API usage examples
  - Best practices
  - FAQ and troubleshooting
  - Audience: Customers, developers using APIs
```

6.3.2 Documentation Standards

```
Format: Markdown with embedded diagrams (Mermaid)
Storage: Git repository with code
Versioning: Same as code versions
Review: Peer review required for all documentation
Automation: Generate API docs from code, diagrams from code
Access: Internal (Confluence), External (Documentation portal)
Maintenance: Owned by development teams, reviewed quarterly
```

