8.2 Power & Cooling Infrastructure

8.2.1 Power Requirements

```
Phase 1 (2025-2026): 100 MW total
  - Quantum Facilities: 50 MW
  - Classical Computing: 30 MW
  - Offices & Labs: 20 MW

Phase 2 (2027-2029): 1 GW total
  - Quantum Facilities: 300 MW
  - Classical Computing: 500 MW
  - Manufacturing: 150 MW
  - Offices & Labs: 50 MW

Phase 3 (2030-2032): 10 GW total
  - Quantum Facilities: 2 GW
  - Classical Computing: 5 GW
  - Manufacturing: 2 GW
  - Carbon Removal: 1 GW
  - Offices & Labs: 0.1 GW

Phase 4 (2033-2035): 100 GW total
  - Quantum Facilities: 10 GW
  - Classical Computing: 30 GW
  - Manufacturing: 20 GW
  - Carbon Removal: 30 GW
  - Climate Intervention: 10 GW
  - Total: 100 GW (0.5% of global electricity)
```

8.2.2 Power Sourcing Strategy

```
Principle: 100% renewable, net negative carbon
Approach: Build own generation where possible, PPAs otherwise

Generation Assets:
  - Solar: 10 GW by 2030, 50 GW by 2035
  - Wind: 5 GW by 2030, 20 GW by 2035
  - Fusion: 0.5 GW by 2032, 10 GW by 2035
  - Geothermal: 1 GW by 2030, 5 GW by 2035
  - Total: 16.5 GW by 2030, 85 GW by 2035

Power Purchase Agreements (PPAs):
  - Strategy: For locations where building not feasible
  - Requirements: 100% renewable, additionality required
  - Term: 10-20 years fixed price
  - Volume: 5 GW by 2030, 15 GW by 2035

Grid Connection:
  - Strategy: Always have multiple grid connections
  - Redundancy: N+2 for critical facilities
  - Quality: Required power quality specifications
  - Backup: On-site generation and storage
```

8.2.3 Cooling Systems

```
Quantum Cooling: Dilution refrigerators
  - Temperature: 10 mK
  - Cooling Power: 1.5 W at 100 mK
  - Reliability: 99.9% uptime requirement
  - Redundancy: N+1 for critical systems
  - Cost: $10M per QE-1024 processor cooling system

Classical Computing Cooling: Direct liquid cooling
  - Approach: Coolant directly to chips
  - Temperature: 45°C inlet, 65°C outlet
  - Flow: 50 L/min per rack
  - Heat Reuse: 90% of heat captured for other uses
  - Efficiency: PUE 1.05

Facility Cooling: Evaporative + free cooling
  - Climate-appropriate: Different solutions per location
  - Water Usage: Zero for water-scarce regions
  - Efficiency: PUE 1.1-1.2 depending on climate
  - Heat Reuse: For nearby buildings or industrial processes
```

8.3 Network Infrastructure

8.3.1 Global Fiber Network

```
Backbone Network: 100 Tbps capacity
  - Routes: Transcontinental, transoceanic
  - Capacity: 100× 1 Tbps lambdas
  - Latency: < 100 ms round-trip globally
  - Resilience: Diverse paths, automatic rerouting
  - Cost: $1B for global backbone
  - Partners: Major telecom carriers + own fiber

Regional Networks: 10 Tbps per region
  - Coverage: Dense fiber within regions
  - Latency: < 10 ms within region
  - Access: To all major data centers and POPs
  - Cost: $100M per major region

Last-Mile Connections: Diverse technologies
  - Fiber: Where available and cost-effective
  - Wireless: 5G/6G for mobile or remote locations
  - Satellite: Starlink/OneWeb for truly remote
  - Power Line: Using grid infrastructure where appropriate
```

8.3.2 Quantum Network

```
Quantum Backbone: 1000 km initially
  - Technology: Quantum key distribution + entanglement distribution
  - Nodes: 100 quantum network nodes
  - Key Rate: 10 Mbps secure key generation
  - Applications: Secure control, grid synchronization
  - Cost: $100M for initial network
  - Timeline: 2026-2027 deployment

Quantum Satellite Links: Global coverage
  - Satellites: 24 LEO satellites with quantum capabilities
  - Purpose: Global quantum key distribution
  - Key Rate: 1 kbps over 1000 km
  - Cost: $500M for constellation
  - Timeline: 2028-2030 deployment
```

