  - H2 2028: Taiwan (semiconductor industry, offshore wind)
  - Coverage: +15 GW, +150 nodes

Phase 3 (2029): Southeast Asia
  - 2029: Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand, Vietnam, Philippines
  - Focus: Rapid grid development, solar integration
  - Coverage: +15 GW, +150 nodes

Phase 4 (2030): China and India
  - 2030: Selected regions in China and India
  - Focus: Massive scale, energy access
  - Coverage: +50 GW, +500 nodes

Total by 2030: 100 GW, 1000 nodes
```

---

11. Operations & Maintenance Framework

11.1 24/7 Operations Center

11.1.1 Global Network Operations Center (GNOC)

```
Primary Centers (3): Colorado, Zurich, Singapore
  - Each: 200 operations personnel
  - Shift Pattern: 3 shifts × 8 hours, 24/7 coverage
  - Redundancy: Any center can handle full load if others fail
  - Connectivity: 10 Gbps to all major nodes

Secondary Centers (3): Backup locations
  - Purpose: Disaster recovery backup
  - Staff: Skeleton crew normally, expandable in emergency
  - Readiness: Can take over within 1 hour

Workstation Configuration:
  - Primary: 6× 4K monitors per operator
  - Secondary: AR/VR headsets for 3D visualization
  - Controls: Custom control panels for critical functions
  - Communication: Integrated voice/video conferencing

Display Wall:
  - Size: 100× 8K panels (50 feet wide × 20 feet high)
  - Content: Global energy flows, system health, alerts
  - Interaction: Touch and gesture controlled
  - Customization: Operator configurable views
```

11.1.2 Monitoring Systems

```
Infrastructure Monitoring:
  - Servers: CPU, memory, disk, network
  - Quantum: Qubit fidelity, coherence times, error rates
  - Neuromorphic: Neuron activity, learning progress, power
  - Network: Latency, packet loss, bandwidth
  - Power: Consumption, quality, temperature
  - Thresholds: Automated alerts when thresholds exceeded

Application Monitoring:
  - Performance: Response times, throughput, errors
  - Business Metrics: Energy optimized, carbon removed, revenue
  - User Experience: API response times, success rates
  - Dependencies: Health of dependent services

Grid Monitoring:
  - Generation: Output, forecasts, availability
  - Load: Consumption, forecasts, patterns
  - Grid Health: Frequency, voltage, stability
  - Market: Prices, volumes, positions
  - Carbon: Intensity, emissions, removals

Security Monitoring:
  - Intrusion Detection: Network and host based
  - Anomaly Detection: Behavioral analysis
  - Vulnerability Scanning: Continuous assessment
  - Compliance Monitoring: Automated compliance checking
```

11.1.3 Alerting and Incident Management

```
Alert Levels:
  - Critical: Immediate human intervention required
  - High: Attention required within 15 minutes
  - Medium: Attention required within 2 hours
  - Low: Attention required within 24 hours
  - Informational: No immediate action required

Alert Routing:
  - Critical: All on-call engineers + management
  - High: Relevant team on-call
  - Medium: Ticketing system for next business day
  - Low: Weekly review

Incident Management:
  - Process: ITIL-based incident management
  - Tools: ServiceNow or similar
  - Escalation: Defined escalation paths
  - Communication: Automated status updates to stakeholders

Post-Incident:
  - Review: Root cause analysis within 24 hours
  - Action Items: Prevent recurrence
  - Documentation: Added to knowledge base
```

11.2 Maintenance Framework

11.2.1 Preventive Maintenance

```
Quantum Processors:
  - Daily: Calibration checks, error rate monitoring
  - Weekly: Full calibration, performance verification
  - Monthly: Cryogenic system maintenance
  - Quarterly: Major calibration, component testing
  - Annually: Full system overhaul, component replacement

Neuromorphic Processors:
  - Daily: Learning progress monitoring
  - Weekly: Performance verification
  - Monthly: Calibration and tuning
  - Quarterly: Full system check
  - Annually: Chip testing and replacement if needed

Edge Nodes:
  - Monthly: Remote diagnostics and health checks
  - Quarterly: On-site inspection (visual, cleaning)
  - Bi-annually: Full functional testing
  - Annually: Component replacement based on predictive analytics

Infrastructure:
  - Daily: Backup verification, log review
  - Weekly: Security updates, performance tuning
  - Monthly: Firmware updates, capacity planning
  - Quarterly: Disaster recovery testing
  - Annually: Full infrastructure review
```

11.2.2 Predictive Maintenance

```
Data Collection:
  - Sensors: Vibration, temperature, electrical characteristics
  - Logs: Error rates, performance degradation
  - Usage Patterns: Load cycles, stress periods
  - Environmental: Temperature, humidity, particulates

Analysis:
  - Machine Learning: Predict failures before they occur
  - Statistical Analysis: Identify patterns leading to failure
  - Root Cause Analysis: Understand why failures occur

Actions:
  - Alerts: Early warning of potential failures
  - Scheduling: Proactive maintenance before failure
  - Spare Parts: Automatic ordering of needed parts
  - Documentation: Lessons learned added to knowledge base

Effectiveness Metrics:
  - Prediction Accuracy: > 90% true positive rate
  - Lead Time: Average 30 days warning before failure
  - Cost Reduction: 50% reduction in unplanned downtime
  - MTBF Improvement: 50% increase in mean time between failures
```

11.2.3 Corrective Maintenance

```
Process:
  - Detection: Automated monitoring detects issue
  - Diagnosis: Automated and manual diagnosis
  - Dispatch: Appropriate technician dispatched
  - Repair: Issue resolved
  - Verification: System tested and verified
  - Documentation: Repair documented

Response Times:
  - Critical: 1 hour response, 4 hour resolution
  - High: 4 hour response, 24 hour resolution
  - Medium: Next business day response
  - Low: Scheduled at convenience

Resources:
  - Field Technicians: 1000+ globally by 2030
  - Spare Parts: Strategically located depots
  - Tools: Specialized for quantum and neuromorphic
  - Knowledge Base: Comprehensive repair procedures

Continuous Improvement:
  - Analysis: Root cause of every failure
  - Prevention: Update preventive maintenance procedures
  - Design: Feedback to design teams for improvements
```

11.3 Support Framework

11.3.1 Customer Support

```
Tiers:
  - Tier 1: Basic support, ticket creation, initial triage
  - Tier 2: Technical support, deeper investigation
  - Tier 3: Engineering support, code-level investigation
  - Tier 4: Hardware support, on-site if needed

Channels:
  - Phone: 24/7 for critical issues
  - Email: For non-urgent issues
  - Chat: For quick questions
  - Portal: For self-service, documentation, ticket management
  - API: For automated support integration

Service Level Agreements (SLAs):
  - Critical: 15 minute response, 1 hour resolution target
  - High: 1 hour response, 4 hour resolution target
  - Medium: 4 hour response, 24 hour resolution target
  - Low: 24 hour response, 5 day resolution target

Metrics:
  - Response Time: Meeting SLA targets
  - Resolution Time: Meeting SLA targets
  - Customer Satisfaction: > 95% satisfied
  - First Contact Resolution: > 70% resolved at first contact
```

11.3.2 Internal Support

```
Development Support:
  - Environments: Provisioning and maintenance of dev/test environments
  - Tools: Development tools and infrastructure
  - Build/Deploy: CI/CD pipeline support
  - Performance: Performance testing support

Data Support:
  - Ingestion: Support for data ingestion pipelines
  - Processing: Support for data processing jobs
  - Storage: Database and storage system support
  - Analytics: Support for analytics and reporting

Security Support:
  - Access: User access management
  - Compliance: Compliance monitoring and reporting
  - Incident Response: Security incident support
  - Education: Security training and awareness

Facility Support:
  - Physical Security: Access control, surveillance
  - Power/Cooling: Infrastructure maintenance
  - Environmental: Monitoring and control
  - Safety: Safety procedures and compliance
```

